---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What causes PSU coil whine?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Coil whine is caused by electromagnetic coils inside the power supply vibrating physically when carrying current. If this vibration matches audible frequencies, you hear a high-pitched buzzing or squealing noise."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is PSU coil whine dangerous?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Coil whine is purely an acoustic annoyance and does not indicate hardware degradation, malfunction, or safety risks."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="PSU Coil Whine: Causes & How to Fix It — PSUCheck"
  description="Understand what causes coil whine in power supplies and graphics cards. Discover safety implications and practical methods to reduce buzzing."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>PSU Coil Whine: Causes &amp; Fixes</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          A high-pitched squeal from your computer can be frustrating.
          This guide explains the causes of PSU coil whine and methods to mitigate it.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>What is Coil Whine?</h2>
          <p>
            Inside your PSU, inductors (coils of wire wound around magnetic cores) act as filters to smooth
            voltages. When current passes through these windings, it creates magnetic fields that cause the wire coils to vibrate.
          </p>
          <p>
            Under heavy loads or high frame rates, these vibrations occur at frequencies within human hearing range, resulting in a high-pitched whine.
          </p>

          <h2>Common Triggers</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>GPU Frame Rates:</strong> Uncapped frame rates in menus (e.g. 500+ FPS) cause rapid GPU transient spikes, inducing resonance in the PSU inductors.</li>
            <li><strong>Electrical Resonance:</strong> Minor mismatch between GPU VRM and PSU switching frequencies.</li>
            <li><strong>House Wiring issues:</strong> High electrical noise on the AC wall input.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Mitigation Methods</h2>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Cap Frame Rates:</strong> Enable V-Sync or set global limits in NVIDIA Control Panel or Radeon Settings to limit extreme current oscillations.</li>
            <li><strong>Use Surge Protection/UPS:</strong> Active line conditioning smooths out AC harmonics entering the PSU.</li>
            <li><strong>Stress Testing:</strong> Often, letting the system run a heavy workload for 24-48 hours can break in the coil adhesives, damping the acoustics over time.</li>
          </ol>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check system acoustics</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/quiet-psu-guide">Quiet PSU Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/single-vs-multi-rail">Single vs Multi Rail</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/how-to-test-a-psu">How to Test a PSU</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
